<subSubSection id="EBCDF5AB773FFFFEFF4EFEF2089F48FA" pageId="4" pageNumber="385" type="description">
<paragraph id="A368A620773FFFFEFF4EFEF20A744B1A" blockId="4.[151,647,294,357]" box="[151,325,331,357]" pageId="4" pageNumber="385">
<figureCitation id="3BECBAA5773FFFFEFF4EFEF20BC24B1A" box="[151,243,331,357]" captionStart="FIGURES 5–28" captionStartId="10.[151,264,2000,2024]" captionTargetBox="[162,1424,185,1973]" captionTargetId="figure-25@10.[158,1430,181,1976]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURES 5–28. Macropsis spp., lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4404165" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4404165/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="385">Figs. 10</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="3BECBAA5773FFFFEFF26FEF20A744B1A" box="[255,325,331,357]" captionStart="FIGURES 48–81" captionStartId="15.[151,264,1893,1917]" captionTargetBox="[183,1402,189,1863]" captionTargetId="figure-16@15.[173,1413,181,1869]" captionText="FIGURES 48–81. Macropsis suspecta (48–54), M. vicina (55–61), M. tarbagataica (62–68), and M. iliensis (69–81). 48–49, 55–56, 62–63―male abdominal apodemes of the 2nd tergite; 50–51, 57–58, 64–65, 69, 71—the 2nd sternite; 52–53, 59–60, 66–67, 70, 72, 74, 77, 80―penis, lateral view; 54, 61, 68, 75, 78, 81―the 2nd valvulae of ovipositor; 73, 76, 79―male 2nd abdominal apodemes. 69–70―paratype of M. iliensis; 71–72―paratype of M. tuvensis." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4457944" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4457944/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="385">62–68</figureCitation>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="A368A620773FFFFEFF4EFE2B0BF54BAE" blockId="4.[151,1437,402,1005]" pageId="4" pageNumber="385">
<emphasis id="91A37A32773FFFFEFF4EFE2B0A184BD3" bold="true" box="[151,297,402,428]" pageId="4" pageNumber="385">Description.</emphasis>
Bright green with yellowish tinge, forewings as a rule slightly infumose, especially in males (
<figureCitation id="3BECBAA5773FFFFEFAB6FE2A0B874BAE" captionStart="FIGURES 5–28" captionStartId="10.[151,264,2000,2024]" captionTargetBox="[162,1424,185,1973]" captionTargetId="figure-25@10.[158,1430,181,1976]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURES 5–28. Macropsis spp., lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4404165" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4404165/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="385">Fig. 10</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="A368A620773FFFFEFF1EFE620E7D481D" blockId="4.[151,1437,402,1005]" pageId="4" pageNumber="385">
Abdominal apodemes of 2 
<superScript id="54A20B68773FFFFEFE28FE6309304B97" attach="left" box="[497,513,474,488]" fontSize="6" pageId="4" pageNumber="385">nd</superScript>
tergite in male as a rule shorter than their width at base, separated by wide notch, more or less rounded, with margins of irregular shape (
<figureCitation id="3BECBAA5773FFFFEFD2DFE46084C4865" box="[756,893,511,538]" captionStart="FIGURES 48–81" captionStartId="15.[151,264,1893,1917]" captionTargetBox="[183,1402,189,1863]" captionTargetId="figure-16@15.[173,1413,181,1869]" captionText="FIGURES 48–81. Macropsis suspecta (48–54), M. vicina (55–61), M. tarbagataica (62–68), and M. iliensis (69–81). 48–49, 55–56, 62–63―male abdominal apodemes of the 2nd tergite; 50–51, 57–58, 64–65, 69, 71—the 2nd sternite; 52–53, 59–60, 66–67, 70, 72, 74, 77, 80―penis, lateral view; 54, 61, 68, 75, 78, 81―the 2nd valvulae of ovipositor; 73, 76, 79―male 2nd abdominal apodemes. 69–70―paratype of M. iliensis; 71–72―paratype of M. tuvensis." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4457944" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4457944/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="385">Figs. 62–63</figureCitation>
). Sternal apodemes approximately triangular, occasionally with more or less prominent projections on inner margins at base (
<figureCitation id="3BECBAA5773FFFFEFC2BFD9A0F4D4842" box="[1010,1148,546,573]" captionStart="FIGURES 48–81" captionStartId="15.[151,264,1893,1917]" captionTargetBox="[183,1402,189,1863]" captionTargetId="figure-16@15.[173,1413,181,1869]" captionText="FIGURES 48–81. Macropsis suspecta (48–54), M. vicina (55–61), M. tarbagataica (62–68), and M. iliensis (69–81). 48–49, 55–56, 62–63―male abdominal apodemes of the 2nd tergite; 50–51, 57–58, 64–65, 69, 71—the 2nd sternite; 52–53, 59–60, 66–67, 70, 72, 74, 77, 80―penis, lateral view; 54, 61, 68, 75, 78, 81―the 2nd valvulae of ovipositor; 73, 76, 79―male 2nd abdominal apodemes. 69–70―paratype of M. iliensis; 71–72―paratype of M. tuvensis." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4457944" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4457944/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="385">Figs. 64–65</figureCitation>
). Penis in side view wide, with indistinct extension in middle (
<figureCitation id="3BECBAA5773FFFFEFDF2FDFE0984481D" box="[555,693,583,610]" captionStart="FIGURES 48–81" captionStartId="15.[151,264,1893,1917]" captionTargetBox="[183,1402,189,1863]" captionTargetId="figure-16@15.[173,1413,181,1869]" captionText="FIGURES 48–81. Macropsis suspecta (48–54), M. vicina (55–61), M. tarbagataica (62–68), and M. iliensis (69–81). 48–49, 55–56, 62–63―male abdominal apodemes of the 2nd tergite; 50–51, 57–58, 64–65, 69, 71—the 2nd sternite; 52–53, 59–60, 66–67, 70, 72, 74, 77, 80―penis, lateral view; 54, 61, 68, 75, 78, 81―the 2nd valvulae of ovipositor; 73, 76, 79―male 2nd abdominal apodemes. 69–70―paratype of M. iliensis; 71–72―paratype of M. tuvensis." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4457944" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4457944/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="385">Figs. 66–67</figureCitation>
). 2 
<superScript id="54A20B68773FFFFEFD0FFDFF09D7482B" attach="left" box="[726,742,582,596]" fontSize="6" pageId="4" pageNumber="385">nd</superScript>
valvulae of ovipositor with 4 preapical teeth (
<figureCitation id="3BECBAA5773FFFFEFB32FDFE0E71481D" box="[1259,1344,583,610]" captionStart="FIGURES 48–81" captionStartId="15.[151,264,1893,1917]" captionTargetBox="[183,1402,189,1863]" captionTargetId="figure-16@15.[173,1413,181,1869]" captionText="FIGURES 48–81. Macropsis suspecta (48–54), M. vicina (55–61), M. tarbagataica (62–68), and M. iliensis (69–81). 48–49, 55–56, 62–63―male abdominal apodemes of the 2nd tergite; 50–51, 57–58, 64–65, 69, 71—the 2nd sternite; 52–53, 59–60, 66–67, 70, 72, 74, 77, 80―penis, lateral view; 54, 61, 68, 75, 78, 81―the 2nd valvulae of ovipositor; 73, 76, 79―male 2nd abdominal apodemes. 69–70―paratype of M. iliensis; 71–72―paratype of M. tuvensis." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4457944" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4457944/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="385">Fig. 68</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="A368A620773FFFFEFF1EFDD2089F48FA" blockId="4.[151,1437,402,1005]" box="[199,942,618,646]" pageId="4" pageNumber="385">
Body length (including tegmina): 
<specimenCount id="B5D16DA9773FFFFEFD9DFDD2096A48FA" box="[580,603,619,645]" pageId="4" pageNumber="385" type="male">♂</specimenCount>
, 
<quantity id="642F0BC5773FFFFEFDBEFDD209C048FA" box="[615,753,619,645]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.05" metricValueMax="4.3" metricValueMin="3.8" pageId="4" pageNumber="385" unit="mm" value="4.05" valueMax="4.3" valueMin="3.8">3.8–4.3 mm</quantity>
; 
<specimenCount id="B5D16DA9773FFFFEFD24FDD2082348FA" box="[765,786,619,645]" pageId="4" pageNumber="385" type="female">♀</specimenCount>
, 4.6–5.0 mm.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="EBCDF5AB773FFFFEFF1EFD360BD1488E" pageId="4" pageNumber="385" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph id="A368A620773FFFFEFF1EFD360BD1488E" blockId="4.[151,1437,402,1005]" pageId="4" pageNumber="385">
<emphasis id="91A37A32773FFFFEFF1EFD360A3748D6" bold="true" box="[199,262,655,681]" pageId="4" pageNumber="385">Host.</emphasis>
In 
<collectingCountry id="DBC0E6B0773FFFFEFEF5FD360A9E48D6" box="[300,431,655,681]" name="Kazakhstan" pageId="4" pageNumber="385">Kazakhstan</collectingCountry>
and Central Asia was found on 
<taxonomicName id="64D7DDA3773FFFFEFCC1FD3608BB48D6" box="[792,906,655,681]" class="Ascidiacea" family="Polycitoridae" genus="Salix" kingdom="Animalia" order="Enterogona" pageId="4" pageNumber="385" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="alba">
<emphasis id="91A37A32773FFFFEFCC1FD3608BB48D6" box="[792,906,655,681]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="385">Salix alba</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(section 
<taxonomicName id="64D7DDA3773FFFFEFC28FD360F1848D6" box="[1009,1065,655,681]" class="Ascidiacea" family="Polycitoridae" genus="Salix" kingdom="Animalia" order="Enterogona" pageId="4" pageNumber="385" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="91A37A32773FFFFEFC28FD360F1848D6" box="[1009,1065,655,681]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="385">Salix</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) and on several species from the section 
<taxonomicName id="64D7DDA3773FFFFEFF29FD0A0A1C48B2" box="[240,301,691,717]" class="Gastropoda" family="Helicidae" genus="Helix" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Stylommatophora" pageId="4" pageNumber="385" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="91A37A32773FFFFEFF29FD0A0A1C48B2" box="[240,301,691,717]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="385">Helix</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. In Southern Urals, 
<collectingCountry id="DBC0E6B0773FFFFEFDC2FD0A095748B2" box="[539,614,691,717]" name="Russia" pageId="4" pageNumber="385">Russia</collectingCountry>
one series of specimens was collected from 
<taxonomicName id="64D7DDA3773FFFFEFBB6FD0A0FC548B2" box="[1135,1268,691,717]" class="Ascidiacea" family="Polycitoridae" genus="Salix" kingdom="Animalia" order="Enterogona" pageId="4" pageNumber="385" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="viminalis">
<emphasis id="91A37A32773FFFFEFBB6FD0A0FC548B2" box="[1135,1268,691,717]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="385">S. viminalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(section 
<taxonomicName id="64D7DDA3773FFFFEFAB9FD0A0BFE488E" authorityName="Gray" authorityYear="1870" class="Anthozoa" family="Ellisellidae" genus="Viminella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Alcyonacea" pageId="4" pageNumber="385" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="91A37A32773FFFFEFAB9FD0A0BFE488E" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="385">Viminella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="EBCDF5AB773FFFFEFF1EFD430FF54922" pageId="4" pageNumber="385" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="A368A620773FFFFEFF1EFD430FF54922" blockId="4.[151,1437,402,1005]" pageId="4" pageNumber="385">
<emphasis id="91A37A32773FFFFEFF1EFD430A50496B" bold="true" box="[199,353,762,788]" pageId="4" pageNumber="385">Distribution.</emphasis>
The whole territory of 
<collectingCountry id="DBC0E6B0773FFFFEFDADFD4209CB496A" box="[628,762,763,789]" name="Kazakhstan" pageId="4" pageNumber="385">Kazakhstan</collectingCountry>
, mountains of Central Asia (Tien Shan and Alay); reaches Southern Urals, 
<collectingCountry id="DBC0E6B0773FFFFEFE97FCA60AA84946" box="[334,409,799,825]" name="Russia" pageId="4" pageNumber="385">Russia</collectingCountry>
in the extreme northwest of the range and 
<collectingCountry id="DBC0E6B0773FFFFEFCA1FCA608D44946" box="[888,997,799,825]" name="Mongolia" pageId="4" pageNumber="385">Mongolia</collectingCountry>
in the extreme northeast. In Southeastern 
<collectingCountry id="DBC0E6B0773FFFFEFF1BFCFA0A744922" box="[194,325,835,861]" name="Kazakhstan" pageId="4" pageNumber="385">Kazakhstan</collectingCountry>
is rather common on willows along riverbanks at the foothills and in the plains.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="EBCDF5AB773FFFFEFF1EFCDE0ABB4992" pageId="4" pageNumber="385" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="A368A620773FFFFEFF1EFCDE0ABB4992" blockId="4.[151,1437,402,1005]" pageId="4" pageNumber="385">
<emphasis id="91A37A32773FFFFEFF1EFCDE0A0A49FE" bold="true" box="[199,315,871,897]" pageId="4" pageNumber="385">Remarks.</emphasis>
Identification of 
<taxonomicName id="64D7DDA3773FFFFEFE22FCDE098149FE" authorityName="Mityaev" authorityYear="1971" box="[507,688,871,897]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Macropsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="385" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tarbagataica">
<emphasis id="91A37A32773FFFFEFE22FCDE098149FE" box="[507,688,871,897]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="385">M. tarbagataica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is based on investigation of a series of 
<typeStatus id="7C6C1882773FFFFEFB87FCDE0FF849FE" box="[1118,1225,871,897]" pageId="4" pageNumber="385">paratypes</typeStatus>
from Southeastern 
<collectingCountry id="DBC0E6B0773FFFFEFF4EFC320A2B49DA" box="[151,282,907,933]" name="Kazakhstan" pageId="4" pageNumber="385">Kazakhstan</collectingCountry>
with the label “Semipalatinsk Oblast [presently the 
<collectingRegion id="611368C2773FFFFEFC84FC320F5A49DA" box="[861,1131,906,933]" country="Kazakhstan" name="Shyghys Qazaqstan Oblysy" pageId="4" pageNumber="385">East Kazakhstan Oblast</collectingRegion>
], Urdzharsk Region, mouth of the Urdzharka [= Urdzhar] River. 
<date id="D76980E0773FFFFEFDEFFC1709F949B6" box="[566,712,942,969]" pageId="4" pageNumber="385" value="1963-06-15">15. VI. 1963</date>
. I. Mityaev” (our comments in square brackets) deposited in the collection of ZMMU.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
